  "prompt": "Does the ISS have a good WiFi connection?",
  "response": "The International Space Station (ISS) does not have WiFi in the traditional sense that we use on Earth. Instead, astronauts use a variety of communication systems to send and receive data, including internet access. \n\nThe primary method for internet access on the ISS is through a system called the \"Space-to-Ground\" communication link, which involves transmitting data via radio waves to a satellite, which then relays the data to a ground station, and finally to the internet. This system can be slower and less reliable than typical home WiFi connections due to the long distances involved and the need to share bandwidth among the crew and various scientific experiments.\n\nIn summary, while the ISS has internet connectivity, it's not what we would typically call a \"good WiFi connection\" by Earth standards due to its reliance on satellite communications and the inherent delays and bandwidth limitations involved.",
